In article <931223005321.080641@DOCKMASTER.NCSC.MIL> (sci.crypt), Grant@DOCKMASTER.NCSC.MIL (Lynn R Grant) writes:
> Commercial traffic has long been forbidden on the ham bands.  So
> if you have a ham radio in your car, it's OK to call your spouse through
> a phone patch to say that you'll be late coming home, but it's not OK
> to call the local pizza joint to order the pizza you're going to pick up
> on the way home.
> 

Actually, it is now legal to order pizza over ham bands. The commercial
use restrictions were recently relaxed by the FCC to better conform with
what people were actually doing (which included ordering pizzas). You still
can't sell and buy, say, stereos over ham bands.

